{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505573"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2456"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2456"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.15,0.18,0.07,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51197"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36469"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1173"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51197"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man is brought in by ambulance to the Emergency Department (ED) after being involved in a motor vehicle accident. He is found to have a traumatic mid-shaft femoral fracture. It is not displaced and after a complete primary and secondary survey he is determined not to have any other major injuries. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/80mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min, SpO2 99% on 2L/min oxygen via nasal cannulae, and temperature 37.5\u00b0C. His Glasgow coma scale score is 15/15. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is in intense pain, rating it a 12/10 currently. He is unable to move his leg at all because of pain. He had 1x Penthrox (methoxyflurane) \u0027whistle\u0027 in the ambulance before arriving in the ED. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA decision was made to prescribe an IV opioid to get him comfortable as rapidly as possible. He weighs 85kgs, has stage 2 chronic kidney disease and does not take any regular medications. He has no allergies. It is decided to prescribe IV fentanyl as this is preferred to morphine in patients with renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should the initial dose of opioids be based on in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Body weight","Pain score","Age","There is a set dose for all adults","Sedation score"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial opioid doses should be based on the age of the patient \u003C/strong\u003E(subsequent doses will depend on effectiveness of that dose and/or side effects).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike other medications, there is \u003Cstrong\u003Eno recommended set dose\u003C/strong\u003E for adults, such as for paracetamol (1g four - six hourly). It is also not based on \u003Cstrong\u003Ebody\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight.\u003C/strong\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESedation scores\u003C/strong\u003E are the key to detecting the onset of opioid-induced ventilatory impairment. They should be done at the time of administration of an immediate-release opioid as well as the expected time to peak effect of that dose. In the case of IV fentanyl, this would be 5 mins after the dose has been given. They do not have a role in determining the initial dose of opioids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epain score\u003C/strong\u003E can help determine the level of subjective pain a patient has together with an assessment of a patient\u0027s functional activity. This thus can help guide which agent/s might be used to help tackle their pain, and high pain score alone should not used to determine the initial dose of opioid or to titrate subsequent opioid doses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with a fractured femur can be hypovolaemic and absorption from a subcutaneous opioid injection may therefore be unreliable. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is a range provided for initial IV opioid doses based on age - generally below and above 70 years of age and not frail or cachetic. For example, IV Fentanyl initial dose is prescribed:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBelow 70 years of age: 15 to 30 micrograms intravenously 5 min PRN\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E70 years of age and above: 7.5 to 15 micrograms intravenously 5 min PRN\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to dose according to this range initially and observe the patient\u0027s response. In this case, the patient would have received between 15 to 30 micrograms intravenously 5 min PRN. When the patient can lie a little more comfortably, a femoral nerve block will also be done.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial doses of opioids should be based on patient age","Sedation score is the most reliable clinician indicator of opioid-induced ventilatory impairment and should be used to titrate subsequent opioid doses"],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. (Internet). AMH. 2022.","Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists and Faculty of Pain Medicine (2023) PS41(G) Position statement on acute pain management. https://www.anzca.edu.au/getattachment/558316c5-ea93-457c-b51f-d57556b0ffa7/PS41(G)-Position-statement-on-acute-pain-management-2023#page=","Therapeutic Guidelines (2020) Pain and Analgesia  https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/guideLine?guidelinePage=Pain+and+Analgesia\u0026frompage=etgcomplete"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36469"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2456"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36469"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-22T09:00:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-27T08:34:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2456"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51197"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":